%FEATURE_STRUCTURES.sofaString:
The female proposita (Fig. 1) was delivered by cesarean at 36 weeks gestation due to breech presentation with normal birth parameters. A two-vessel umbilical cord, hypertelorism and a wide metopic suture were noted at birth. Her hearing and newborn metabolic screening tests were unremarkable and she was discharged from the hospital on day 4 of life.

She was referred to Genetics at 5 months for hypertelorism. Growth and development were normal at that time. She had a widow's peak, mild frontal bossing and a widened metopic suture. She had telecanthus and ocular hypertelorism, with an inner canthal distance (ICD) of 3.5 cm (≫97th centile), interpupillary distance (IPD) of 5.2 cm (≫97th centile) and outer canthal distance (OCD) of 8.2 cm (≫97th centile). The nasal bridge was broad and the nasal tip was bifid. Her ears were slightly low-set. The philtrum was relatively long and the mouth had slightly downturned corners. Her neck was normal and there was no chest deformity. She had a small, dystrophic left fifth toenail, but her digits and nails were otherwise unremarkable.

A cranial ultrasound performed at 2 months of age had shown no abnormalities other than a right choroid plexus cyst and a left ependymal cyst. Skull radiographs showed no evidence of craniosynostosis and further cranial imaging was declined.
